WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.840
All right, well, good morning, everybody. My name is Marcus. I am the senior scientist

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:11.600
at the Tampa Bay Estuary Program. And I'm going to be talking about what arguably was

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:17.959
the most stressful six months of my life. So I really felt that keynote this morning.

00:00:17.959 --> 00:00:22.959
This is really about data science under stress and how do you make decisions when there's

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:30.440
a sense of urgency around those decisions. So we're going to do the retrospective approach

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:37.279
here. If you go back to July of 2021, I live in Tampa Bay. That's where I work. If you

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:43.279
were to walk around the shores of Tampa Bay, you'd notice these really conspicuous dumpsters

00:00:43.279 --> 00:00:49.959
with a sign out in front of them that said dead fish only. It's really gross. There were

00:00:49.959 --> 00:00:56.279
dead fish all along the shoreline, right? So there was like a massive fish kill that

00:00:56.279 --> 00:01:01.279
had happened in Tampa Bay. So many fish that the powers that be didn't really know what

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:06.120
to do about it. So the city was like, we'll just put out these dumpsters. The public can

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:12.480
clean it up. It was out of control. I actually looked in the dumpster. Zero of ten. Would

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:19.680
not recommend. It was disgusting. But it was just a gnarly situation. And so a couple months

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:24.720
earlier, what was kind of leading up to this event, there's this facility on the southeast

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:31.559
shore of Tampa Bay called Piney Point. It is a legacy fertilizer processing plant. Long

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:36.639
story short, there's a convoluted history as to why this facility exists, why it led

00:01:36.639 --> 00:01:42.680
to this emergency discharge. But there was really a leak in the holding tanks for the

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:47.680
wastewater that was sitting on site for years. And to prevent, you know, issues with public

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:52.279
safety and destruction of public property, the best decision at that time was to release

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:58.320
all of that water into the bay to prevent catastrophic failure of the stacks. This was

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:04.919
a couple months prior to the fish kill. Nobody wanted this to happen. It was not ideal. And

00:02:04.919 --> 00:02:10.880
this water was nasty. You know, very acidic, excess nutrients, all that bad stuff. Over

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:15.720
a ten-day period when they were releasing this water, that part of the bay received

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.039
an amount of pollution that it normally would have received in a year. So we expected all

00:02:20.039 --> 00:02:27.479
sorts of negative outcomes to occur. And to further underscore the horrific nature of

00:02:27.479 --> 00:02:33.080
this event, my boy Stephen King was tweeting about this. Back when Twitter was a thing,

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:38.880
I used to follow him. And he's quite witty. But I think he has a vacation home in Florida.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:44.779
So he often would tweet about Florida-based things. And needless to say, this was receiving

00:02:44.820 --> 00:02:49.979
national attention, given that, you know, there was an expected negative outcome from

00:02:49.979 --> 00:02:59.820
this event. So I work in environmental science. I'm the only data scientist on my team. And

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:03.940
we knew that this event was going to have a negative effect on the bay. And everybody

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:08.820
that was involved, the public, environmental managers, policy makers, really wanted to

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:16.020
know, obviously, how is this going to affect the environmental resources in Tampa Bay?

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:20.259
From the environmental management perspective, they wanted to know where are the conditions

00:03:20.259 --> 00:03:26.139
going to be the worst? So where do they focus their efforts for, say, cleaning up dead fish?

00:03:26.139 --> 00:03:30.419
And we also just had a general need to understand what can we do about it? Like, what can we

00:03:30.419 --> 00:03:35.059
learn from the situation so that if it were to happen again, how do we sort of mitigate

00:03:35.059 --> 00:03:41.020
it or even prevent it? And this is a time of crisis, right? So these are questions that

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:46.740
were important, but they needed the answers right now. So that was really the main issue

00:03:46.740 --> 00:03:52.740
here, is we knew negative outcomes were going to occur, but we needed to know what was happening

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:57.899
at that moment to inform the response in a concerned public.

00:03:57.899 --> 00:04:02.940
So an alternative title that I was thinking for this talk was good enough crisis management,

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:08.259
you know, one thing I learned about data science coming to this conference is that we're really

00:04:08.259 --> 00:04:12.699
concerned with efficiency and refactoring everything to make it as good as possible

00:04:12.699 --> 00:04:16.179
as the best product we can make. That's not what this talk is about. This is about doing

00:04:16.179 --> 00:04:22.619
scrappy data science when you want to get information out there as fast as possible.

00:04:22.619 --> 00:04:28.899
So my program where I work at, we facilitate a lot of the management, the decisions around

00:04:28.899 --> 00:04:34.500
how Tampa Bay is managed. We facilitated this response-based monitoring effort that

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:40.820
was dozens of agencies going out there collecting data, hundreds of sites where they were going

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:46.059
out collecting information, dozens of parameters they were looking at, and as an environmental

00:04:46.059 --> 00:04:53.059
scientist, tens of thousands of measurements is a lot for me. So a lot of good data that

00:04:53.299 --> 00:04:57.940
was being collected, but of course we all know data is not information. So that needed

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:03.619
to be distilled. So I'll cut to the chase here. We produced a dashboard. This is, you

00:05:03.619 --> 00:05:07.579
know, the end product here. This is how we distilled it. We were quite happy with this

00:05:07.579 --> 00:05:14.179
product. It was useful for the public as well as decision makers and policy makers. But

00:05:14.179 --> 00:05:18.700
it took a lot to go from that data set to the dashboard.

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:25.500
I appreciated the last talk kind of showing a similar example. This is like the scenario

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:30.459
that keeps data scientists up at night. You just have tons of data files coming in. This

00:05:30.459 --> 00:05:36.619
was the situation we were in. We were the only organization at the time that was synthesizing

00:05:36.619 --> 00:05:40.779
this information. And I said, please, just give it to me. I'll deal with it. And if you

00:05:40.779 --> 00:05:46.459
look at that scroll bar on the right there, it goes down and down.

00:05:46.459 --> 00:05:52.339
So this is the situation we were in. Quickly my dumpster was on fire, and I needed to distill

00:05:52.339 --> 00:05:57.059
this information as rapidly as possible. So this is a common, like, workflow that I

00:05:57.059 --> 00:06:01.700
think many data scientists are familiar with. But this is kind of how I set this up. This

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:06.940
is a gross overview of what this actually is. But we said, give us your data, put it

00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:10.459
on Google Drive, we'll deal with it. So it was great. We were getting the information

00:06:10.459 --> 00:06:16.100
or rather getting the data. But, of course, all that data needed to be synthesized into

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:21.540
a format that was able to be basically pushed up to the dashboard. So I was in the trenches

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:26.579
this entire time basically synthesizing this information. Then it was pushed up to GitHub.

00:06:26.579 --> 00:06:32.899
It was run through a suite of tests to verify the accuracy of that data. And then ultimately

00:06:32.899 --> 00:06:36.940
pushed to the dashboard. So this is what I was doing, basically synthesizing the data

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:44.739
and pushing it to GitHub and then the dashboard. So this is the good enough crisis management.

00:06:44.739 --> 00:06:52.540
So going back to this idea of efficiency that we think about as data scientists, I

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:58.899
wrote a ton of code just making the raw data from Google Drive into a format that could

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:06.179
be pushed up to GitHub and then the dashboard. This is code I'm not proud of. It's not pretty.

00:07:06.179 --> 00:07:12.859
It's not efficient. Sure, it could be improved. This is, you know, like me hand coding a lot

00:07:12.859 --> 00:07:19.260
of the renames for the stations. But this code worked. It did what I needed it to do.

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:22.500
I was hand coding a lot of stuff. It could have been better. But I did not spend a lot

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:29.380
of time refactoring this code because I just simply didn't have that time to do that. So

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:36.140
I'm embarrassed of this code, but it worked. Where I wasn't going to sacrifice attention

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:40.980
was the accuracy of the information coming out of that data synthesis workflow. And so

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:47.100
as sort of an insurance policy that I set up for myself, when the data came out of that

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:51.899
workflow, it was pushed to GitHub and I set up a series of tests using test that. This

00:07:51.899 --> 00:07:55.380
isn't your conventional testing that you would do for like a package, but these are things

00:07:55.380 --> 00:08:00.420
I wrote to verify that the data coming out of that workflow that I produced wasn't garbage.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:04.540
So are the names correct? Are the measurements in range? Are there duplicate values? Things

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:09.220
like that. So was the data that I was churning out following the schema that I developed

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:14.899
that was appropriate for the dashboard? These are my guardrails. This is the most important

00:08:14.899 --> 00:08:19.980
piece of this talk, I think, is this is where I did not sacrifice attention because I knew

00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:23.820
that the data coming out of this workflow had to be accurate and had to be something

00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:26.700
that would be useful on the dashboard. So I'm going to look at this a little bit more

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:31.579
carefully. This is just by the numbers over basically the six-month period from the discharge

00:08:31.579 --> 00:08:38.140
release to when conditions sort of improved. There are 641 commits to GitHub. Among those

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:44.219
commits, there were about 8,500 tests. And the good news is a large majority of those

00:08:44.219 --> 00:08:48.580
tests passed. So my workflow, even though it was ugly, was churning out data that I

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:54.580
was happy with. However, a small minority of those tests failed. And this is small in

00:08:54.580 --> 00:09:01.179
the grand scheme of things, but these tests that failed saved my ass in a lot of instances.

00:09:01.179 --> 00:09:06.340
And I'm going to show you what that looked like. So if these tests were not in place,

00:09:06.979 --> 00:09:10.260
the obvious thing that would happen is we would break the dashboard. And this is a Flex

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:15.340
dashboard, so we would get this Pandoc error if we pushed data that was not compatible

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:19.059
with the dashboard. Obviously, we don't want to do this. We don't want to break the dashboard.

00:09:19.059 --> 00:09:25.820
It looks bad. Also, it's not serving the users. So it caught these instances where we would

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:31.539
simply break the dashboard. But I think more importantly, it did catch more insidious issues

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:38.580
that wouldn't necessarily break the dashboard, but would lead to us showing inaccurate information

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:42.940
that could lead to wrong decisions about how to respond to this event. And so this is an

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:49.419
example where I'm showing basically just a couple days of data where I have chlorophyll

00:09:49.419 --> 00:09:54.700
A, which is sort of a proxy for water quality. The points are sized by the concentration.

00:09:54.700 --> 00:09:58.460
So you can think of the points, the bigger the points, the worse the water quality, very

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:04.580
generally speaking. These small points here, these are actually instances where the units

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:11.739
of those points mismatched what my schema was meant to be. So when the data was provided

00:10:11.739 --> 00:10:17.900
to me, it was different units. And what happens is because the units were different, the data

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:22.619
basically shows up as NA values on the dashboard. They're still shown. This is a location, but

00:10:22.619 --> 00:10:29.460
there's no value associated with it. So this basically prevents or provides a false indication

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:33.380
of water quality by showing these points. Because they're small, it looks like water

00:10:33.380 --> 00:10:39.020
quality is actually better than it actually is. And so the tests were able to identify

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:44.460
that. And if it wasn't there, I would have pushed these points to the dashboard and provided

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:51.219
a false sense of water quality that, of course, we didn't want to do.

00:10:51.219 --> 00:10:55.619
So what was kind of interesting when I was preparing this talk, we went through the speaker

00:10:55.619 --> 00:10:59.820
coaching, and one of the questions I got from one of the other speakers was when you're

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:04.219
developing a front-facing dashboard, obviously you want to work with your users, get their

00:11:04.219 --> 00:11:09.659
feedback on how to, you know, suit their needs, basically meet them where they're at. How

00:11:09.659 --> 00:11:15.700
did we do this in a time of crisis? So obviously, you know, the naive developer envisions this

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:22.380
ideal scenario where, hey, I made this awesome thing for you. That's great. The user says,

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:26.299
I love this, but can you please change this one part? And then you say, yeah, sure, no

00:11:26.299 --> 00:11:31.219
problem, I'll fix it for you, and everyone's happy. I realized the first keynote had a

00:11:31.219 --> 00:11:36.820
similar slide. I made this before him, so it was my idea first. But this is an ideal

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:42.700
scenario. We know it doesn't work like that. It's more like this, where, you know, step

00:11:42.739 --> 00:11:47.820
one of whatever, you get some requests that make sense, some that are about incorporating

00:11:47.820 --> 00:11:54.260
data, some are just not helpful, and others are just downright mean.

00:11:54.260 --> 00:12:01.260
So we wanted to avoid this. You know, I was busy developing that synthesis workflow, creating

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:06.580
the tests. I didn't have time to filter all of the requests and address the user needs.

00:12:06.739 --> 00:12:13.820
Oh, and my heart was broken in this example. So what we did, and this is not something

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:17.659
that is ideal when you're developing a product, but in a time of crisis, I think this is really

00:12:17.659 --> 00:12:23.380
important. I had what I'm calling champion allies, right, that served as a buffer between

00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:28.460
the users and me. And essentially, this was my boss and the assistant director. They were

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:32.539
also in the trenches, talking to the media, talking to the public, so they had their finger

00:12:32.539 --> 00:12:36.619
on the pulse of what was actually happening. But what they could do for me is, you know,

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:41.380
while I was in my cave developing the app, they could filter, you know, obviously the

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:46.539
nonsense requests. They also, I've worked with them for a long time, so they know what

00:12:46.539 --> 00:12:51.780
I can accomplish. So a request could have been valid, but given the urgency of this,

00:12:51.780 --> 00:12:57.260
wasn't worth the amount of time. And they also, most importantly, know the science.

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:01.960
So they know, you know, what water quality is all about. They know what type of information

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:06.400
needs to be displayed for it, and they can then filter the most appropriate requests

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:11.440
down to me. So I was insulated, and I could focus on what I needed to focus the most on

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:18.200
and have my champion allies buffer me from all of this extra noise while I was creating

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:24.559
these things. This is just a short GIF of the dashboard, just to show you what it looked

00:13:24.559 --> 00:13:29.479
like. A lot of stuff on there. I'm going to show you some of the water quality results.

00:13:29.479 --> 00:13:33.919
You can click through multiple parameters. Here we're looking again at chlorophyll A.

00:13:33.919 --> 00:13:38.599
What's cool is you can toggle that and see which ones are quickly out of the normal range

00:13:38.599 --> 00:13:44.159
for that time of year and location, and you can zoom in and get more detailed information

00:13:44.159 --> 00:13:48.719
about individual sites. So this is a time series, and then again, showing that context

00:13:48.719 --> 00:13:54.960
of what is normal. So you can see that things are kind of out of whack.

00:13:54.960 --> 00:14:00.400
And we also, if we hadn't had this workflow in place, we wouldn't be able to create infographics

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:04.760
like this. And this is so important to my program, where we're kind of in the business

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:08.760
of storytelling in a way, where we interact with the public and we want to tell a narrative

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:13.479
about environmental health and environmental quality. And had we not had this workflow

00:14:13.479 --> 00:14:19.039
to support this narrative or this infographic, we wouldn't be able to tell this story. So

00:14:19.039 --> 00:14:23.039
this is something the public can see and look at and, you know, quickly understand what

00:14:23.039 --> 00:14:28.440
happened, but it is data supported, and it's supported by data that we were able to synthesize

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:36.719
and make sense of using this workflow. We know it was reaching its end users. So again,

00:14:36.719 --> 00:14:41.479
back when Twitter was a thing, we were getting some attention. Charlie Justice, he was the

00:14:41.479 --> 00:14:45.679
chair of our policy board, county commissioner at the time. He was giving us unsolicited

00:14:45.679 --> 00:14:50.119
advertising for the dashboard. And it was also really cool, the media was picking up

00:14:50.119 --> 00:14:53.799
on this. We weren't actively reaching out to the media, but because we were doing open

00:14:53.799 --> 00:15:00.880
science and pushing graphics on GitHub, they were finding them and using them and developing

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:07.359
a narrative. So this is a newscast where this is one of my graphics here that I created.

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:11.559
It's pretty funny. If you go to that link, you'll see a video of me being interviewed

00:15:11.559 --> 00:15:17.760
where I really needed a haircut. But again, this is what I love to see happen when you're

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:22.840
doing data science. You want people to use this information. To me, this is the best

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:26.640
example of how this can be done or how this was done.

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:33.840
Fortunately, you know, this was a couple years ago. Piney Point is currently being closed.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:40.080
Obviously the work I did was not the sole reason why this place is finally being closed

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:46.359
down, but I do like to think that some of the work we did did help. It did help the

00:15:46.359 --> 00:15:51.840
conversation around what it means to manage these facilities responsibly and shed a light

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:58.479
on how they can really have negative impacts when they're not managed responsibly.

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:03.239
So I think this is, you know, pretty straightforward. Again, this was, like, how do we do data science

00:16:03.239 --> 00:16:09.479
when there's, like, tremendous sense of urgency? Obviously you can't focus on everything, triage,

00:16:09.479 --> 00:16:14.440
what's important, prioritize your time. But when you do make these shortcuts, use the

00:16:14.440 --> 00:16:19.919
guardrails, because they will save you. Like I said, the testing that I did was just instrumental

00:16:19.919 --> 00:16:25.159
to making sure we didn't break things or push inaccurate information that could lead to

00:16:25.159 --> 00:16:29.799
wrong decisions. And finally, get those champions as expert

00:16:29.799 --> 00:16:34.119
allies that can help you with what you're doing. I'm the only data scientist on the

00:16:34.119 --> 00:16:40.000
team, but they were so instrumental to me to help me do the work that I needed to do

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.280
when everyone was sort of running around in chaos at the time.

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:50.239
So that's it. Those are my champions. Shout out to them. I want to thank PositConf for

00:16:50.239 --> 00:16:53.840
giving me the time to talk about this, and appreciate your time, and I'll take questions

00:16:53.840 --> 00:16:55.440
if there's time.

00:16:55.440 --> 00:17:04.319
Thank you so much, Marcus. One question here. Do you have suggestions on how to test for

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:08.520
data quality issues that you don't necessarily expect to occur?

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:13.359
That's a very good question, because the things I coded for were things that I expected

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:18.439
to occur. And I'll say, you know, I know some of that information that was getting out there

00:17:18.439 --> 00:17:23.280
was not perfect. A good example is I was, you know, what's common with water quality

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:29.880
data is you have replicate measurements or lab blanks that are meant to be like QC information

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:34.079
that typically doesn't go on a dashboard. I was pushing some of that information up

00:17:34.079 --> 00:17:38.560
there. It wasn't wrong information. It was just QC data. And what was cool is because

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:43.760
this was a high-profile dashboard, the data provider actually called me and was like,

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:48.319
hey, you know, you're pushing QC data to the dashboard, just FYI. So I don't have a good

00:17:48.319 --> 00:17:56.199
answer to that. We know it wasn't perfect, but it met our needs at the time.

00:17:56.199 --> 00:18:03.719
Great. Could you expand on test that capabilities that you used for the dashboard? Maybe briefly?

00:18:04.359 --> 00:18:13.000
Yeah. So I'm not a database manager or database engineer. I kind of developed my ad hoc schema

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.839
of what I wanted the data to look like. So it was in that unified format. And I basically

00:18:17.839 --> 00:18:24.640
developed the tests around that. And it also looked for really egregious things like negative

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:29.560
values for dissolved oxygen. It can't go negative, for example. So there's some obvious cases,

00:18:29.560 --> 00:18:35.560
but it was also supported by decades of monitoring data that we have for the region that gives

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:40.599
context of what is normal, what is abnormal. And we sort of, we try to incorporate some

00:18:40.599 --> 00:18:44.920
of that knowledge into the testing as well. So it was informed by my experience as well

00:18:44.920 --> 00:18:49.920
as just what was feasible or physically impossible.

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:56.439
Amazing. Together with your champion allies, could you give a quick suggestion on anything

00:18:56.560 --> 00:19:01.000
you've learned about managing user requests, considering that you've probably got a lot

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.040
of them if the dashboard was public?

00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:10.079
Yeah. When we developed this dashboard, we kind of flipped the process on its head. It

00:19:10.079 --> 00:19:16.479
was a situation where this information needed to get out there ASAP. So I just pushed something

00:19:16.479 --> 00:19:22.959
out there. I think it was out there within four days of the release starting. So we had

00:19:22.959 --> 00:19:27.000
information out there because there was a concerned public, decision makers. So we didn't

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:32.520
have the time to incorporate user requests like you normally would or the intentional

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:39.800
design process where you kind of meet their needs and where they're at.

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:44.199
So I'll say we kind of just went at it in sort of an ad hoc way and did the best we

00:19:44.199 --> 00:19:50.959
could. And I think the proof of concept that it was being picked up by the media, it was

00:19:50.959 --> 00:19:54.560
something I tweeted about. I had analytics running on it too. I know people were using

00:19:54.560 --> 00:20:00.760
it. And I would go to talks and see screen grabs of the dashboard. So I had a good sense

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:05.119
that it did what we wanted it to do. We just had to be really intentional with the types

00:20:05.119 --> 00:20:07.560
of requests we were getting from users.

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:09.160
Awesome. Thank you so much.

